# Why legacy-peer-deps:
#
# `openai@4.x` declares a peer dependency on `zod@^3.23.8`. We ship `zod@^4`
# everywhere else in this project (Editor / API / template validators).
# npm 7+ defaults to strict peer-dep resolution and bails the install with
# ERESOLVE. The conflict is *declarative only*: OpenAI's runtime code never
# touches zod (we use `chat.completions.create` directly, not its zod-based
# helpers like `responses.parse`), so the practical risk is zero.
#
# `legacy-peer-deps=true` tells npm to fall back to the npm 6 behavior of
# warning about peer-dep mismatches instead of erroring. Vercel and CI both
# read this file automatically, so the build goes through without a `--force`
# flag in the build command.
#
# When OpenAI SDK v5 (which broadens the peer to `^3 || ^4`) becomes the
# stable choice for our usage pattern, drop this file.
legacy-peer-deps=true
